We first discuss the case of an unwalled cell. After sufficient cycles of osmotic oscillation, the internal state (ρ~p,ηa) egin{document}$ (	ilde{ho}_{p},\eta_{a})$\end{document} converges to a periodic steady state that lies on ρ~pηa=1 egin{document}$ 	ilde{ho}_{p}\eta_{a}=1$\end{document} (Appendix 1—figure 2E). After removing the oscillatory stimulus, the internal state leaves the curve ρ~pηa=1 egin{document}$ 	ilde{ho}_{p}\eta_{a}=1$\end{document} and returns to this curve after fully adapting to the reference growth media. During this adaptation process, the internal osmotic pressure constantly equals the external one because the turgor pressure is zero. Therefore, setting Π˙in=0 egin{document}$ \dot{\Pi}_{in}=0$\end{document} in Equation A17, the free-volume growth rate takes the form of(A18)μf=μrηaρ~p. egin{document}$$\displaystyle 
